{"count": 41724, "next": "https://api.acmi.net.au/works/?page=1921", "previous": "https://api.acmi.net.au/works/?page=1919", "results": [{"id": 100294, "acmi_id": "E000056", "title": "Type 2014K Image Orthicon camera", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "pye-image-orthicon-black-and-white-studio-camera-model-2014-k-mounted-on-tripod-with-vinten-heavy-duty-skid-type-412", "creator_credit": "Films & Equipment Ltd., PYE Ltd. and Vinten", "credit_line": "<p>ACMI Collection</p>", "headline_credit": "United Kingdom, c. 1950", "video_links": [], "record_type": "work", "type": "Object", "is_on_display": true, "last_on_display_place": "ACMI: Gallery 1", "last_on_display_date": "2031-02-16", "is_context_indigenous": false, "material_description": "", "unpublished": false, "external": false, "first_production_date": null, "commissioned": false, "public_domain": false, "external_references": [], "brief_description": "<p>Pye cameras were used across Australia in newsrooms and in the field by journalists at GTV9 and ABV2. They are lightweight and compact, making them easy to transport, and they feature an extended focus range switch for extreme close-ups.</p>", "constellations_primary": [{"id": 253, "name": "News on location", "description": "The Pye Orthicon is an example of the type of television cameras used from the 1950s in Australia for both studio and outside broadcast work. Such cameras did not have have the capacity to record while out on location and so outside crews would transmit vision and sound back to studios for recording or live broadcast."}], "constellations_other": [], "recommendations": [], "creator_credit_for_label": "<p>Films &amp; Equipment Ltd., PYE Ltd. and Vinten</p>", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>United Kingdom, c. 1950</p>", "title_for_label": "<p>Type 2014K Image Orthicon camera</p>", "description": "<p>In 1948, Australian audiences were introduced to television at the Sydney Royal Easter Show. The British electronics company Pye had brought its 405-line cameras and monitors to encourage interest in the new medium.</p>\n<p>While it would be eight years until Bruce Gyngell famously welcomed Australia to television, the Pye company was still essential to the burgeoning industry.</p>\n<p>Pye cameras like this were used across Australia in newsrooms and in the field by journalists at GTV9 and ABV2. They are lightweight and compact, making them easy to transport, and they feature an extended focus range switch for extreme close-ups.</p>", "description_for_label": ["<p>In 1948, Australian audiences were introduced to television at the Sydney Royal Easter Show. The British electronics company Pye had brought its 405-line cameras and monitors to encourage interest in the new medium.</p>\n<p>While it would be eight years until Bruce Gyngell famously welcomed Australia to television, the Pye company was still essential to the burgeoning industry.</p>\n<p>Pye cameras like this were used across Australia in newsrooms and in the field by journalists at GTV9 and ABV2. They are lightweight and compact, making them easy to transport, and they feature an extended focus range switch for extreme close-ups.</p>"], "credit_line_for_label": "<p>ACMI Collection</p>", "details": [{"label": "Curatorial section", "display_values": ["The Story of the Moving Image&nbsp;→ Moving Pictures&nbsp;→ MI-06. Language of Film&nbsp;→ MI-06-C01"]}, {"label": "Measurements", "display_values": ["175 x 122 x 122cm"]}, {"label": "Object Types", "display_values": ["Camera/ Camera crane / Camera lens/Film and television equipment"]}], "stats": {"tap_count": 202673}, "links": [], "creators_primary": [{"id": 2639016, "name": "Films & Equipment Ltd.", "creator_id": 71967, "creator_wikidata_id": null, "role": "manufacturer", "role_id": 627, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2639013, "name": "PYE Ltd.", "creator_id": 71965, "creator_wikidata_id": null, "role": "manufacturer", "role_id": 627, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2639014, "name": "Vinten", "creator_id": 71966,